m the banking industry, quantitative data, and research findings as well as personal stories from interviews with indebted families around the country, Delinquent provides a relatable and humane entry into understanding debt. Botella exposes the ways that bank marketing, product design, and customer management strategies exploit our common weaknesses and fantasies in how we think about money, and she also demonstrates why competition between banks has failed to make life better for Americans in debt. Delinquent asks: How can we make credit available to those who need it, responsibly and without causing harm? Looking to the future, Botella presents a thorough and incisive plan for reckoning with and reforming the industry.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aBanks and bankingzUnited States. 0aConsumer creditzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Workplace Culture.2bisacsh  abad credit.  acredit card.  acredit score.  acredit use.  acrisis.  adebt collection.  adebt.  aeconomics.  afaud.  afinances.  agood credit.  ahardships.  amarket value.  apoverty.  aself help.  avalue.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Business and Economics 2022 Englishz978311099282308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics 2022z9783110992922oZDB-23-DBV08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076649340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520380363?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520380363423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/97